  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I find the URL of a picture?",
  "response": "To find the URL of a picture, you typically need to use a web browser. Here are the steps you can follow:\n\n### On a Computer:\n1. **Open the web page** where the picture is located.\n2. **Right-click** on the picture. This will open a context menu.\n3. Select **\"Open image in new tab\"** or **\"Copy image address\"** from the context menu.\n   - If you select \"Open image in new tab\", go to the new tab that opens; the URL in the address bar is the URL of the picture.\n   - If you select \"Copy image address\", the URL of the picture will be copied to your clipboard, and you can paste it wherever you need.\n\n### On Mobile Devices:\n- **Android**:\n  1. **Open the web page** where the picture is located.\n  2. **Tap and hold** on the picture until a menu appears.\n  3. Select **\"Open image in new tab\"** or **\"Copy link address\"**.\n\n- **iOS**:\n  1. **Open the web page** where the picture is located using Safari or another browser.\n  2. **Tap and hold** the picture until a menu appears.\n  3. Select **\"Open Image\"** or **\"Copy\"** option.\n  4. You might need to navigate to the newly opened tab to find the image URL in the address bar if you selected \"Open Image\". If you copied the link, it will be in your clipboard ready to be pasted.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- Make sure that the image is not embedded in a way that prevents direct access to its URL (like certain protected content).\n- If the image is inside a slideshow or gallery, right-clicking might not give a direct image URL. Look for options in the gallery interface or the direct opening of the image.\n\nUsing these steps will help you easily obtain the direct URL of an image from various web sources.",
